'''Luka Rocco Magnotta''' (born '''Eric Clinton Kirk Newman'''; July 24, 1982) is a Canadian murderer who was convicted of killing and dismembering Lin Jun, a Chinese [[international student]], before mailing Jun's hands and feet to elementary schools and federal political party offices.{{r|rewind}} This act gained international notoriety. After a video depicting the murder was posted online in May 2012, Magnotta fled Canada, becoming the subject of an [[Interpol Red Notice]] and prompting an international [[Manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunt]]. In June 2012, he was apprehended at an [[Internet café]] in [[Berlin]] while reading news about himself.{{r|rewind}} In December 2014, after eight days of deliberations, a jury convicted him of first-degree murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/12/23/luka_magnotta_is_convicted_of_firstdegree_murder.html#|title=Luka Magnotta is convicted of first-degree murder|work=thestar.com}}</ref> He was previously sought by [[animal rights]] groups for uploading videos of himself killing [[kitten]]s.{{r|5th}}

==Biography==
===Early life===
Magnotta was born Eric Clinton Kirk Newman{{r|CBC_timeline}} on July 24, 1982, in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough, Ontario]] to Anna Yourkin and Donald Newman, one of three children. According to him, his mother was obsessed with cleanliness, would routinely lock her children out of the house, and once put her children's pet rabbits out in the cold to freeze to death. His father was diagnosed with schizophrenia in 1994,<ref name="mongazpsych">{{cite web |last1=Montgomery |first1=Sue |title=Psychiatrist's report chronicles the making of Luka Magnotta |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/psychiatrists-report-chronicles-the-making-of-luka-magnotta |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=29 September 2018 |date=14 November 2014}}</ref> after which he divorced his wife, leading to Magnotta later moving in with his grandmother, Phyllis.{{r|CBC_timeline}} Both his grandmother and younger brother, Conrad, would often call him "faggot" for his effeminate tendencies.

He attended [[I. E. Weldon Secondary School]] in [[Lindsay, Ontario|Lindsay]].{{r|CBC_timeline}}

In 2003, he began to appear in [[pornography|pornographic]] videos, occasionally working as a [[stripper]] and a [[male escort]].{{r|CBC_timeline|MSN_interview}} He appeared as a pin-up model in a 2005 issue of Toronto's ''[[fab (magazine)|fab]]'' magazine using the pseudonym "Jimmy".{{r|Xtra_Jimmy}} In 2007, he was an unsuccessful competitor in [[OutTV (Canada)|OUTtv]]'s reality series ''[[COVERguy]]''.{{r|TS_audition|Sun_Coverguy|Xtra_details}} Magnotta had multiple [[Cosmetic surgery|cosmetic surgeries]] and auditioned for the [[Slice (TV channel)|Slice network]] television show ''Plastic Makes Perfect'' in February 2008.{{r|Shaw_Plastic}}

===Early criminal activity===
In 2005, he was convicted of one count of impersonation and three counts of fraud (against [[Sears Canada]], [[The Brick]], and 2001 Audio Video) after impersonating a woman to apply for a credit card and purchasing over $10,000 worth of goods. He pleaded guilty and received a nine-month [[Conditional sentence (Canada)|conditional sentence]] with 12 months of probation.{{r|GM_glimpse|CBC_timeline}} He legally [[Name change|changed his name]] to Luka Rocco Magnotta on August 12, 2006.{{r|CBC_whois}} Magnotta declared [[bankruptcy]] in March 2007, owing $17,000 in various debts.{{r|VS_bankruptcy|CTV_whois}} The bankruptcy was fully discharged in December 2007.{{r|VS_bankruptcy}}

Magnotta created many profiles on various Internet [[social media]] and [[Internet forum|discussion forums]] over several years to plant a variety of claims about himself.{{r|CBC_whois|CTV_whois}} One such rumor emerged in 2007, claiming Magnotta was in a relationship with [[Karla Homolka]], a high-profile Canadian convicted murderer, though he denied this in a subsequent interview with the ''[[Toronto Sun]]''.{{r|Macleans_Homolka|Sun_Homolka|Warmington-2012-05-31}} During the murder investigation, Montreal police initially announced the pair had dated but soon retracted the statement and acknowledged that they had no evidence to corroborate the claim.{{r|Macleans_Homolka}} As with the Homolka relationship, Magnotta repeatedly denied the claims he himself had planted as hoaxes and part of a campaign of [[cyberstalking|cyber stalking]] against him.{{r|CBC_whois}} Police stated that Magnotta set up at least 70 [[Facebook]] pages and 20 websites under different names.{{r|Macleans_FB}} According to the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]], Magnotta posted on the white supremacist website [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]] under two different usernames, and had followed the Twitter account of white nationalist [[Don Black (white nationalist)|Don Black]]. In one of his alleged Stormfront comments, Magnotta denounced Chinese people.<ref name="splc1">{{cite web|url=http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2014/summer/White-Homicide-Worldwide|title=White Homicide Worldwide|last=Beirich|first=Heidi|date=Summer 2014|work=Intelligence Report,|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>

==Murder of Lin Jun==
Lin Jun ({{zh|c=林俊|p=Lín Jùn}}) (30 December 1978 – 24/25 May 2012), also known as Justin Lin, was an [[international student]] from [[Wuhan]] and an undergraduate in the engineering and computer science faculty at [[Concordia University]].{{r|CBC_id}} He worked part-time as a convenience store clerk in [[Pointe-Saint-Charles]].{{r|TS_denial}} Lin had been studying in [[Montreal]] since July 2011.{{r|CBC_id}} Lin moved into a [[Griffintown]]-area apartment with a roommate on May 1.{{r|CBC_id}} He was last seen on May 24, 2012, and his friends reported getting a text message from his phone at 9 pm.{{r|TS_denial}} His boss became suspicious when he didn't show up for his shift the next day.{{r|CBC_friends|CN_shift}} Three of his friends went into his apartment on May 27.{{r|TS_denial|CTV_id|CN_shift}} He was reported missing to police on May 29.{{r|CBC_id|CTV_id}}

On May 25, 2012, an 11-minute video titled ''1 Lunatic 1 Ice Pick'' was uploaded to [[Bestgore.com]], depicting a naked male tied to a bed frame being repeatedly stabbed with an [[ice pick]] and a kitchen knife, then [[dismemberment|dismembered]], followed by acts of [[necrophilia]].{{r|NP_video|TS_gore}} The perpetrator uses a knife and fork to cut off some of the flesh and gets a dog to chew on the body.{{r|NP_video|DB_nom}} During the video, the 1987 [[New Order (band)|New Order]] song "[[True Faith (song)|True Faith]]" plays in the background,{{r|NP_video}} and a poster for the 1942 film ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' is visible on the wall.{{r|TS_horror}} Canadian authorities obtained a "more extensive" version of the video and said [[cannibalism]] may have been performed.{{r|TS_schools|MG_nom}} Materials promoting the video appeared online 10 days before the murder took place.{{r|OC_refs|NP_promo}}

On May 26, an attorney from [[Montana]] attempted to report the video to [[Toronto Police Service|Toronto Police]], his local [[Sheriffs in the United States|Sheriff]], and the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]], but the report was dismissed by officials.{{r|CBC_report|TS_video}} Bestgore viewers also attempted to report the video.{{r|CBC_bestgore}} Police later confirmed it as authentic and identified the victim, an Asian male, as the same one whose body parts were sent to Ottawa.{{r|GM_apt}}

At 11 am on May 29, 2012, a package containing a left foot was delivered to the national headquarters of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]].{{r|NP_manhunt}} The package was stained with blood and had a foul smell.{{r|NP_Byrne|CC_trauma}} It was marked with a red [[Heart (symbol)|heart]] symbol.{{r|GM_apt}} Another package containing a left hand was intercepted in a [[Canada Post]] processing facility, addressed to the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]].{{r|GM_apt}} A janitor discovered a decomposing [[torso]] inside a suitcase, left in a garbage pile in the alley behind an apartment building in the [[Snowdon, Montreal|Snowdon]] area of Montreal.{{r|NP_manhunt}} He first saw the suitcase on May 25, but it was not picked up due to the large amount of garbage that day.{{r|GM_apt}}

After searching the scene, police recovered human remains, bloody clothes, papers identifying the suspect, as well as "sharp and blunt objects" from the back alley.{{r|CBC_police2}} Footage from [[surveillance cameras]] inside the building showed a suspect bringing numerous garbage bags outside, and the images matched the suspect who was captured on video at the post office in [[Côte-des-Neiges]].{{r|CBC_police2}}

At 11:33 pm [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] (03:33 [[UTC]]), police searched apartment 208 of the building, which Magnotta was renting.{{r|CBC_police2}} He had moved in four months prior, and his rent was paid up to June 1.{{r|TS_apt}} The apartment had been mostly emptied before he left.{{r|TS_apt}} Blood was found on different items including the mattress, the refrigerator, the table, and the bathtub.{{r|TS_apt}} "If you dont [sic] like the reflection. Dont [sic] look in the mirror. I dont [sic] care" was written in red ink on the inside of a closet.{{r|TS_apt}}

On May 30, 2012, it was confirmed that the body parts belonged to the same individual, later identified as Lin Jun.{{r|CTV_id}} The suspect in the case was quickly identified as Magnotta, who had by then fled.{{r|CTV_id}}

A note was found with the package sent to the Conservative Party, saying six body parts had been distributed and the perpetrator would kill again.{{r|CTV_note}} The other three packages also contained notes, but their contents were undisclosed by police, who cited their concerns about possible [[copycat crimes]].{{r|CBC_probe}}

On June 5, 2012, a package containing a right foot was delivered to [[St. George's School (Vancouver)|St. George's School]] and another package containing a right hand to [[False Creek Elementary School]] in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia.{{r|TS_schools|AP_schools}} Both schools opened as normal the following morning.{{r|VC_crisis|CBC_probe}} It was confirmed that both packages were sent from Montreal.{{r|CBC_probe}}

On June 13, the four limbs and the torso were matched to Lin using [[DNA profiling|DNA]] samples from his family.{{r|NP_match}} On July 1, his head was recovered at the edge of a small lake in Montreal's [[Angrignon Park]] after police received an anonymous tip.{{r|CTV_head}}

Lin's body was [[cremation|cremated]] on July 11 and his ashes were buried on July 26 at [[Notre Dame des Neiges Cemetery]] in Montreal.{{r|CBC_funeral|MG_funeral|DM_funeral}}

==Manhunt==
An [[arrest warrant]] for Magnotta was issued by the [[Service de police de la Ville de Montréal]] (SPVM), later upgraded to a Canada-wide warrant{{r|RCMP}} by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP), accusing him of the following crimes:{{r|CBC_warrant}}
# [[Murder (Canadian law)#Murder|First-degree murder]];
# Committing an indignity to a dead body;
# Publishing obscene material;
# Mailing obscene, indecent, immoral or scurrilous material; and
# Criminally harassing Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and several (unnamed) members of Parliament.

On May 31, 2012, [[Interpol]] issued a [[Red notice]] for Magnotta at the request of Canadian authorities, and for several days before and after his arrest his name and photo were displayed prominently at the top of the home page of the Interpol website. The Red Notice requested that Magnotta be provisionally arrested pending extradition back to Canada by any [[Interpol#Members|Interpol member state]].{{r|Interpol_2}}

Magnotta booked a ticket for a flight from Montreal to Paris on May 25, using a passport with his own name.<ref name=passport>{{cite news|last=Shivji|first=Salimah|title=Luka Magnotta trial hears from ex-PM's son and Karla Homolka's sister|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-trial-hears-from-ex-pm-s-son-and-karla-homolka-s-sister-1.2803849|accessdate=19 October 2014|work=CBC News |date=17 October 2014}}</ref> After his arrival in France, his cell phone signal was traced to a hotel in [[Bagnolet]], but he had left by the time police arrived.{{r|AFP_hotel}} Pornographic magazines and an air-sickness bag were found in the hotel room.{{r|AFP_hotel|CBC_coverage}} Magnotta used a false passport with the name "Kirk Trammel" at the hotel.<ref name=hotel>{{cite news|title=Luka Rocco Magnotta: Victim's family meets Montreal police|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2012/06/06/luka_rocco_magnotta_victims_family_meets_montreal_police.html|accessdate=19 October 2014|work=Thestar.com|date=6 June 2012}}</ref> He had contacts in Paris from a previous visit in 2010, and police were following a large-framed man who had been in contact with Magnotta.{{r|AP_schools}} Another man he stayed with for two nights did not realize who he was until he had left.{{r|AP_schools}} Magnotta then boarded a [[Eurolines]] bus at the Bagnolet coach station bound for [[Berlin]], Germany.{{r|AP_schools}}

On June 4, 2012, Magnotta was apprehended by [[Berlin Police]] at an [[Internet café]] in the [[Neukölln]] district while reading news stories about himself.{{r|CBC_arrest}} He tried giving fake names before admitting who he was.{{r|CBC_arrest}} His identity was confirmed through [[fingerprint]] evidence.{{r|CBC_arrest}} Magnotta appeared in a Berlin court on June 5, 2012.{{r|Reuters_German}} According to German officials, he did not oppose his extradition.{{r|Reuters_German}} There was sufficient evidence to keep him in custody until extradition,{{r|NP_match}} and he agreed to a simplified process.{{r|CBC_family}}

On June 18, 2012, Magnotta was delivered to Canadian authorities in Berlin and flown aboard a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] [[CC-150 Polaris]] to [[Mirabel International Airport]], north of Montreal. A military transport was reported by the government to be necessary due to safety concerns with using a commercial flight and potential legal difficulties if the plane was diverted to another country.{{r|CTV_flight}} He was placed into [[solitary confinement]] at the [[Rivière-des-Prairies, Quebec|Rivière-des-Prairies]] detention centre.{{r|Sun_isolation}}

==Immediate aftermath==
Reactions in China were highly critical, with some believing the murder was racially motivated.{{r|Y_C}} Some Chinese questioned public safety in Canada, as the killing was the second high-profile murder of a Chinese student there in slightly over a year.{{r|Y_C}} [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Canada)|Foreign Affairs Minister]] [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]] called Chinese ambassador Zhang Junsai ({{lang|zh|章均赛}})<!--Source for Chinese: https://web.archive.org/web/20120305175415/http://ca.china-embassy.org/chn/sgxxx/dsjlx/ / https://www.webcitation.org/6QMxA5dBh?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20120305175415/http://ca.china-embassy.org/chn/sgxxx/dsjlx/ --> to convey his condolences.{{r|The Huffington Post}}

On June 4, 2012, Canadian [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] said he was pleased that the suspect was arrested and congratulated the police forces on their good work in apprehending him.{{r|CBC_arrest}} Interim [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] leader [[Bob Rae]] said that Canadians should mourn the victim rather than "in any way, shape or form" celebrate Magnotta's notoriety.{{r|CBC_arrest}}

Two days later, Lin Jun's family arrived at [[Montréal-Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Trudeau Airport]] in Montreal.{{r|CBC_family|TS_family|VS_family}} The [[Chinese Students and Scholars Association]] of [[Concordia University]] established a fund to defray expenses incurred by Lin's family while in Canada and an award was created in his honor.{{r|Sun_unity|GM_fund|CBC_award}} A [[candlelight vigil]] was held in Montreal.{{r|GM_vigil|CTV_vigil}}

Magnotta was named [[Canadian Newsmaker of the Year]] by [[The Canadian Press]], which caused controversy.{{r|GM_newsmaker|newsmaker}}

On July 16, 2013, Edmonton police charged [[Bestgore.com]] owner Mark Marek with corrupting public morals, a rarely used [[obscenity]] charge, for posting the ''1 Lunatic 1 Ice Pick'' video online.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/story/2013/07/17/edmonton-best-gore-marek-charged.html Gore site owner charged over video in Magnotta case] CBC News, July 17, 2013. Retrieved July 18, 2013.</ref> On January 25, 2016, Marek changed his plea to guilty and was sentenced to a six-month conditional sentence after a joint submission from the Crown and defence. He had to serve half of the six-month sentence under house arrest.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Global News]]|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2474806/edmonton-gore-website-owner-on-trial-for-posting-magnotta-video/|title=Edmonton gore website owner sentenced for posting Magnotta video|date=25 January 2016}}</ref>

==Legal proceedings==

===Preliminary hearing===
On June 19, Magnotta appeared in court by [[videotelephony|video link]] to plead not guilty to all charges through his lawyer.{{r|AJ_plea}} On June 21, Magnotta appeared in person at a high-security Montreal courtroom to request a [[trial by jury]].{{r|Sun_jury}}

A [[preliminary hearing]] began on March 11, 2013. The evidence presented is subject to a [[publication ban]]. Magnotta's defence team requested the media and the public be barred entirely from the hearing; this was declined the next day.{{r|Reuters_public}} Lin Jun's father, Lin Diran, travelled from China to attend the hearing.{{r|Sun_father}} On March 13, one of Magnotta's lawyers resigned, due to a possible [[conflict of interest]].{{r|Gazette_conflict}} Expert witnesses testified, including a [[Forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]], a [[forensic toxicology|forensic toxicologist]], a [[forensic odontology|forensic odontologist]],{{r|Gazette_experts}} a [[bloodstain pattern analysis|bloodstain analyst]],{{r|Sun_blood}} [[data recovery]] specialists{{r|LP_three}} and an Internet investigations officer.{{r|OC_collapse}} The prosecution also displayed video evidence.{{r|LP_three}} Both Magnotta and Lin physically collapsed at separate times during the proceedings.{{r|Gazette_emo|Sun_blood|OC_collapse}}

On April 12, 2013, Magnotta was indicted on charges of first-degree murder, offering indignities to a human body, distributing obscene materials, using the postal service to distribute obscene materials, and criminal harassment.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/04/12/luka-magnotta-preliminary-hearing-trial-decision.html | work=CBC News | title=Luka Magnotta to stand trial on 1st-degree murder – Montreal – CBC News}}</ref>

===Trial===
Magnotta elected to be tried by judge and jury.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He pleaded not guilty, admitting to the acts of which he was accused but claiming [[diminished responsibility]] due to mental disorders. [[Crown Attorney]] Louis Bouthillier made his [[opening statement]] on September 29, 2014. [[Quebec Superior Court]] Justice Guy Cournoyer presided over the trial, which lasted 10 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|last1=CBCNews|title=Luka Magnotta guilty of 1st-degree murder in Jun Lin's slaying|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-guilty-of-1st-degree-murder-in-jun-lin-s-slaying-1.2875989|website=CBC News - Latest Canada, World, Entertainment, and Business News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> On the opening day, he instructed jurors that Magnotta "admits the acts or the conducts underlying the crime for which he is charged. Your task will be to determine whether he committed the five offences with the required state of mind for each offence."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-trial-hears-how-torso-found-in-trash-outside-apartment-1.2781112|title=Luka Magnotta trial hears how torso found in trash outside apartment|date=September 29, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=September 30, 2014}}</ref>

Six tools (a pair of scissors, two knives, a screwdriver, an oscillating saw and a hammer) were recovered outside Magnotta's apartment and analysed by ballistics expert Gilbert Desjardins. He said none could be definitively linked to the killing, and no skeletal marks suggested the screwdriver or scissors were used, but some were consistent with saw and knife or X-Acto blade injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/crown-s-last-in-person-witness-testifies-at-luka-magnotta-trial-1.2072934|title=Crown's last in-person witness testifies at Luka Magnotta trial|work=CTVNews}}</ref>

During the trial, defence attorney Luc Leclair argued that Magnotta was in a psychotic state at the time of the crimes and couldn't be held responsible for his actions. The Crown prosecutor argued that the murder of Jun Lin was organized and premeditated and that Magnotta was "purposeful, mindful, ultra-organized and ultimately responsible for his actions."<ref name=seq/>

Magnotta chose not to testify during the trial.<ref name=seq/>

After a 12-week trial which included 10 weeks of hearing testimony, the jury of eight women and four men received final instructions from the trial judge on December 15, 2014, and was sequestered before beginning its deliberations the next day.<ref name=seq>{{cite news|title=Luka Magnotta trial: Jury now sequestered|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-trial-jury-now-sequestered-1.2871549|accessdate=December 15, 2014|work=CBC News|date=December 15, 2014}}</ref> On their eighth day of deliberation, they returned a verdict of guilty on all charges.<ref name=convicted>{{cite news|title=Luka Magnotta trial: Jury delivers guilty verdict in death of Jun Lin|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-trial-jury-delivers-guilty-verdict-in-death-of-jun-lin-1.2875989|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=CBC News|date=December 23, 2014}}</ref> Magnotta will serve a mandatory life sentence and will be eligible for parole in 25 years. He was also sentenced to 19 years for other charges, to be served concurrently.<ref>Michael Winter (December 23, 2014). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/12/23/canada-killing-dismemberment-life-sentence/20825699/ "Canadian guilty of killing, dismembering Chinese student."] ''[[USA Today]]''. Retrieved December 24, 2014.</ref>

Magnotta filed an appeal for the convictions to be annulled and new trial ordered. The appeal was filed with the Quebec Court of Appeal by Magnotta's defence counsel Luc Leclair, citing judicial error in jury instruction. The appeal further claimed that the "verdicts are unreasonable and unsupported by the evidence and the instructions."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-files-appeal-of-murder-conviction-1.2918352 |title=Luka Magnotta files appeal of murder conviction |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=2015-01-19 |accessdate=2015-02-09}}</ref> Magnotta withdrew his appeal on February 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-withdraws-appeal-of-1st-degree-murder-conviction-1.2961348 |title=Luka Magnotta withdraws appeal of 1st-degree murder conviction |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=2015-02-18 |accessdate=2015-02-18}}</ref>

===Mental health===
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;"
|+ '''Trial Expert Testimony'''
|-
