During his trial for murder, defence witnesses provided evidence that Luka Magnotta had been diagnosed with [[paranoid schizophrenia]] as a teenager.<ref name=MG>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Allison|title=Luka Magnotta diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia, 2005 court document say|url=https://montrealgazette.com/Luka+Magnotta+diagnosed+with+paranoid+schizophrenia+2005+court+document+says/8189128/story.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=17 July 2014}}</ref> Defence expert Dr. Joel Watts testified that Magnotta showed signs of episodic schizophrenia (undifferentiated type), [[histrionic personality disorder]], borderline personality traits and [[paraphilia]] not otherwise specified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/2014/11/17/psychiatrist-downplays-e-mail-magnottas-sister-told-him-about|title=Magnotta in the mirror fails to faze defence psych|author=Daly, Brian|publisher=Brantford Expositor|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref> The prosecution revealed that Magnotta had been using illegal drugs during his teenage years which led to symptoms that mimicked schizophrenia and that Magnotta has been diagnosed with [[borderline personality disorder]] by Crown expert Dr. Joel Paris at Jewish General Hospital in Montreal in April 2012.<ref name=SM>{{cite news|last1=MONTGOMERY|first1=Sue|title=Psychiatrist's report chronicles the making of Luka Magnotta|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/psychiatrists-report-chronicles-the-making-of-luka-magnotta|accessdate=29 December 2014|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=14 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=f1>{{cite web|title=Luka Magnotta File|url=http://postimg.org/image/8s02w1u41/|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=f2>{{cite web|title=Luka Magnotta File 2|url=http://postimg.org/image/4bdjsrm0r/|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> Dr. Renée Roy, the forensic psychiatrist who has been treating Magnotta at Rivières-des-Prairies Detention Centre since November 2012, through his preliminary hearing and right up to the murder trial, diagnosed Magnotta with borderline personality disorder with histrionic features.<ref name=RD>{{cite news|last1=DiManno|first1=Rosie|title=DiManno: A strange trip through Luka Magnotta's medical history|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/11/03/dimanno_a_strange_trip_through_luka_magnottas_medical_history.html|accessdate=29 December 2014|publisher=The Toronto Star|date=3 November 2014}}</ref> Dr. Gilles Chamberland, another Crown expert who was not able to interview Magnotta, diagnosed Magnotta with [[antisocial personality disorder|anti-social]], histrionic and [[narcissistic personality disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/national/its-not-his-illness-its-his-personality-magnotta-trial-told|title=It's not his illness, it's his personality, Magnotta trial told|author=Montgomery, Sue|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=December 1, 2014|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref> A number of psychiatrists over the years noted that Magnotta displayed antisocial, borderline, histrionic, and narcissistic traits. The prosecution accused Magnotta of [[Malingering|pretending]] to be schizophrenic since his defence pleaded [[diminished responsibility]] due to alleged schizophrenia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/luka-magnotta-didn-t-act-like-a-schizophrenic-person-psychiatrist-says-1.2852607|title=Luka Magnotta didn't act like a schizophrenic person, psychiatrist says|date=November 27, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Daly |first=Brian |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/11/27/ultra-organized-magnotta-didnt-seem-schizophrenic-says-crown-expert |title=Personality disorder best explains Luka Magnotta: Crown expert &#124; Magnotta trial |publisher=Torontosun.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-09}}</ref>

==Investigation into other possible crimes==
Magnotta is alleged to be the person behind a series of videos of [[Cruelty to animals|animal cruelty]] involving cats which were posted to [[YouTube]] beginning in 2010, including one titled "1 boy 2 kittens" which showed a man deliberately suffocating two kittens with a vacuum cleaner.{{r|CC_kittens}} In January 2011 a private Facebook group identified Magnotta as the person in these videos;{{r|huffpobarbi}} animal rights activist groups subsequently offered a $5,000 reward for bringing him to justice.{{r|CBC_timeline}} In February 2011, Toronto police began investigating Magnotta in connection with the videos after receiving a complaint from the [[Ontario Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]]{{r|GM_kittens}} The OSPCA also contacted the [[Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] in England, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigations|FBI]], and police in Montreal due to the suspect's extensive travels.{{r|GM_kittens}}

Alex West, a journalist for British tabloid newspaper ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', met Magnotta while he was living in London in 2011, following claims that he had made "Python Christmas", an online video showing a kitten being eaten alive by a [[Burmese python]].{{r|LS_look}} ''The Sun'' contacted [[Scotland Yard]], which denied that the python video incident had occurred within its jurisdiction, stating that the video had been "posted from somewhere in North America".{{r|LS_mirror}} Following his meeting with Magnotta, Alex West said he received a threatening email, which he believed was sent by Magnotta.{{r|Sun_AlexWest}}

On June 8, the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] announced they were in contact with Montreal police to determine if Magnotta was involved in the then-unsolved murder and decapitation of Hervey Medellin,{{r|abc6812|Obs_LAPD|Gazette_LAPD}} known as the "Hollywood Sign Murder", but later announced that they did not believe he was involved in the crime.{{r|LA cops}} The animal rights group [[Last Chance for Animals]] claimed responsibility for posting YouTube videos linking him to the Hollywood Sign Murder in an attempt to lure Magnotta into contacting them.{{r|LCA_edge|Obs_LCA|Fox_LCA}} LCA offered a $7500 reward for information leading to his arrest while he was on the run.{{r|LCA_reward}} On November 16, 2015, Gabriel Campos-Martinez was sentenced to 25 years to life for the murder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-life-in-hollywood-body-parts-case-20151116-story.html |title=Man gets 25 years to life in Hollywood sign body parts murder |website=Los Angeles Times |last1=Winton |first1=Richard |date=16 November 2015 |accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>

The case also drew comparisons across North America to [[Mark Twitchell]], a convicted murderer inspired by ''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]'', who used social media in his crimes and to self-promote his work.<ref name=twitchell /> Author [[Steve Lillebuen]], who wrote a book on the case, described a new trend in crime where social media allows killers to become "online broadcasters" and have direct, instant access to a global audience they may crave.<ref name=steve /><ref name=steve2 />

